# Prisma Migrations & Permissions

## New permissions MUST go in migrations, not seed.ts

When a feature requires new RBAC permissions, add them as SQL `INSERT` statements
inside the migration file — NOT in `seed.ts`.

The seeder is only for first-time environment bootstrapping. Production deployments
run `prisma migrate deploy` and never re-run the seeder.

```sql
-- ✅ GOOD: in migration.sql — applied automatically on every environment
INSERT INTO "permissions" ("id", "name", "category", "created_at", "updated_at")
VALUES (gen_random_uuid(), 'feature:read', 'Category', NOW(), NOW())
ON CONFLICT ("name") DO NOTHING;

-- Grant to Admin and Super Admin roles
INSERT INTO "role_permissions" ("role_id", "permission_id", "created_at", "updated_at")
SELECT r.id, p.id, NOW(), NOW()
FROM "roles" r, "permissions" p
WHERE r.name IN ('Admin', 'Super Admin')
  AND p.name = 'feature:read'
ON CONFLICT ("role_id", "permission_id") DO NOTHING;
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD: adding permissions only in seed.ts
// Production won't pick these up without manually re-running the seeder
{ name: 'feature:read', category: 'Category' },
```

## Migration commands

- **Development:** `npx prisma migrate dev` (creates + applies migrations, generates client)
- **Production / CI:** `npx prisma migrate deploy` (applies pending migrations only, no prompts, no resets, no seed)

NEVER run `prisma migrate dev` in production.

## Migration file conventions

- Prisma auto-generates the schema DDL. Append data-seeding SQL (permissions, reference data) at the end of the generated file.
- Always use `ON CONFLICT ... DO NOTHING` for idempotency.
- Use `gen_random_uuid()` for new UUIDs (PostgreSQL built-in).
